    "title": "What is Menopause?",
    "summary": "Think of menopause as the \"reverse\" of puberty. Just as your body changed when you were a teenager to prepare you for the possibility of having children, menopause is the natural process where your body transitions ou...",
    "content": "The Big Picture\n\nThink of menopause as the \"reverse\" of puberty. Just as your body changed when you were a\nteenager to prepare you for the possibility of having children, menopause is the natural process\nwhere your body transitions out of that stage. It is a normal part of aging, not a disease or a\n\"medical problem.\"\n\nHow is it defined?\n\nIn the medical world, you have officially reached menopause when you have gone 12\nconsecutive months without a menstrual period. Before you reach that 12-month mark, you\nare in a transition phase called Perimenopause. This is when your periods might become\nirregular—sometimes heavy, sometimes light, or skipping months. In Nepal, many women call\nthis \"the time the blood stops,\" but it is actually a years-long process of change.\n\nWhat is happening inside?\n\nYour ovaries (the part of your body that releases eggs) slowly stop producing two main\nhormones: Estrogen and Progesterone.\n\n   ● Estrogen is like a \"super-messenger\" for women. It doesn't just control periods; it\n      helps keep your bones strong, your heart healthy, and your brain sharp.\n   ● As these hormone levels drop, your body has to learn how to function with less of them.\n      This \"adjustment period\" is what causes the symptoms people talk about, like feeling hot\n      or being moody.\n\nWhen does it usually happen in Nepal?\n\nWhile the global average is 51, research shows that in Nepal, the average age is around 48 to\n49 years old. * Early Menopause: If it happens between ages 40 and 45.\n\n   ● Premature Menopause: If it happens before age 40. (If this happens, it is very important\n      to see a health professional).\n\nWhy does this information matter?\n\nUnderstanding menopause helps you take control. When you know that a sudden feeling of\nheat or a burst of anger is caused by a hormonal shift and not \"all in your head,\" it reduces\nstress. It allows you to say, \"My body is changing, and that is okay.\"\n\n      Quick Tip: Menopause isn't \"the end.\" It is the start of a new life stage where your\n      body moves its energy away from reproduction and toward long-term wellness.",
