    "title": "What are the common symptoms of menopause?",
    "summary": "Think of your body like a radio that has been tuned to a specific station (Estrogen) for thirty years. Suddenly, the signal is getting weaker. As the signal fades, your body experiences \"static.\" This static is what w...",
    "content": "The \"Why\" Behind the Change\n\nThink of your body like a radio that has been tuned to a specific station (Estrogen) for thirty\nyears. Suddenly, the signal is getting weaker. As the signal fades, your body experiences\n\"static.\" This static is what we call symptoms.\n\nBecause estrogen travels to almost every part of your body—your brain, your skin, your heart,\nand your bones—you might feel changes in places you didn't expect.\n\n1. The \"Heat Wave\" (Hot Flashes & Night Sweats)\n\nThis is the most famous symptom. You might suddenly feel a wave of heat starting in your chest\nand moving to your face.\n\n   ● What it feels like: Your face might turn red, and you might start sweating even if the\n      room is cold.\n   ● At Night: If this happens while you sleep, it’s called a \"night sweat.\" You might wake up\n      with damp clothes or sheets.\n\n2. The \"Mood Rollercoaster\"\n\nMany women in Nepal feel extra irritable or sad during this time. You might find yourself getting\nangry at small things or crying for no clear reason.\n\n   ● Why it happens: Hormones help regulate the \"feel-good\" chemicals in your brain. When\n      hormones drop, your mood can shift quickly. It is not because you are a \"bad\" person or\n      \"weak\"; it is biological.\n\n3. Changes in Your Cycle\n\nBefore your periods stop completely, they will likely change.\n\n   ● The Pattern: They might come every 2 weeks, or every 3 months. They might be very\n      heavy or very light. This is your body’s way of \"winding down.\"\n\n4. \"Brain Fog\" & Sleep Issues\n\nDo you find yourself walking into a room and forgetting why you went there? Or lying awake at\n3:00 AM?\n\n   ● Forgetfulness: This is often called \"brain fog.\" It feels like your mind is a bit cloudy.\n   ● Sleep: Low hormones can make it hard to stay asleep, which makes you feel even more\n      tired the next day.\n\n5. Physical Aches and Dryness\n\n   ● Joint Pain: You might feel stiff in the mornings, especially in your knees or fingers.\n   ● Skin & Hair: Your skin might feel drier, and your hair might become thinner.\n\nWhen should I see a doctor?\n\nWhile these symptoms are \"normal,\" you should seek help if:\n\n   1. Your periods are so heavy you have to change a pad every hour.\n   2. Your sadness feels so heavy that you cannot do your daily work.\n   3. You have pain that makes it hard to walk or sleep.",
