    "title": "Can menopause affect my memory (Alzheimer's)?",
    "summary": "Have you ever walked into a room and completely forgotten why you went there? Or struggled to remember a common word like \"keys\" or \"umbrella\"? ● In Nepal, many women worry they are \"losing their minds\" or getting \"ol...",
    "content": "What is \"Brain Fog\"?\n\nHave you ever walked into a room and completely forgotten why you went there? Or struggled\nto remember a common word like \"keys\" or \"umbrella\"?\n\n   ● In Nepal, many women worry they are \"losing their minds\" or getting \"old\" too fast.\n   ● Actually, up to 60% of women experience this during menopause. It is often called\n      Brain Fog.\n\nThe Estrogen Connection\n\nYour brain is filled with tiny \"docking stations\" for estrogen. When estrogen levels are high, it\nhelps your brain:\n\n   1. Burn energy efficiently.\n   2. Protect brain cells from damage.\n   3. Stay \"sharp\" and focused.\n\nWhen estrogen levels drop during menopause, your brain has to find a new way to process\nenergy. This transition is what causes that \"cloudy\" or \"fuzzy\" feeling in your head.\n\nThe Link to Alzheimer’s Disease\n\nAlzheimer’s is a disease that causes severe memory loss later in life. Statistics show that\ntwo-thirds of people with Alzheimer’s are women. * The Good News: Most \"menopause\nbrain fog\" is not Alzheimer’s. For most women, the foggy feeling goes away once their body\nadjusts to the new hormone levels.\n\n   ● The Research: Scientists believe that the loss of estrogen might make the brain more\n      vulnerable to Alzheimer's later on. This is why taking care of your brain now is so\n      important.\n\nHow to Keep Your Brain Healthy\n\nYou can help protect your brain during and after menopause with these simple steps:\n\n   ● Learn Something New: Keep your brain \"exercising\" by reading, learning a new craft,\n      or playing memory games.\n   ● Prioritize Sleep: Your brain \"cleans\" itself while you sleep. Lack of sleep makes brain\n      fog much worse.\n\n  ● Stay Social: Talking to friends and family in your community keeps your brain active and\n     happy.\n  ● Eat Brain Foods: Foods like walnuts, fish, and leafy green vegetables (like Saag) are\n     great for brain health.\n\n    Key Takeaway: If you are forgetful right now, don't panic. It is likely a temporary\n    side effect of your hormones changing. However, staying active and healthy now is\n    the best \"insurance\" for your brain’s future.",
