    "language": "english",
    "title": "How do I talk to my family about how I’m feeling?",
    "summary": "You might feel that it is easier to \"just get on with it\" and keep your struggles to yourself. However, when you don't talk about what you are going through, your family might misunderstand your behavior. ● If you are...",
    "content": "Why Talking Matters\n\nYou might feel that it is easier to \"just get on with it\" and keep your struggles to yourself.\nHowever, when you don't talk about what you are going through, your family might\nmisunderstand your behavior.\n\n   ● If you are irritable, they may think you are angry at them.\n   ● If you are forgetful, they may think you are not paying attention.\n   ● If you are tired, they may think you are lazy.\n\nTalking about menopause isn't \"complaining\"—it is giving your family a map to understand the\nchanges in your body.\n\n1. Choose the \"Right\" Time\n\nDon't try to have this conversation in the middle of a hot flash or while you are busy cooking\ndinner.\n\n   ● Find a quiet moment: When things are calm, like after dinner or during a walk.\n   ● Start simple: You don’t need to use medical words. Try saying, \"I’ve been feeling a bit\n      different lately because my body is going through some natural changes, and I wanted to\n      share that with you.\"\n\n2. Explain the \"Why\" (The Science of Mood)\n\nExplain that your hormones are shifting, and these hormones affect your emotions.\n\n   ● For your partner: \"I might feel extra tired or upset sometimes. It’s not because of\n      anything you did; it’s just my body adjusting to new hormone levels.\"\n   ● For your children: \"Mom might need a little more rest or quiet time right now because\n      my body is working hard to stay healthy. It’s like when you feel tired during a growth\n      spurt.\"\n\n3. Be Specific About What You Need\n\nYour family wants to help, but they often don't know how. Give them small, clear tasks:\n\n   ● \"It would really help me if you could take over the evening dishes so I can rest.\"\n   ● \"When I feel a hot flash starting, I just need five minutes to sit by the fan without being\n      asked questions.\"\n\n   ● \"If I seem a bit frustrated, please just give me a little patience. It will pass.\"\n\n4. Normalizing the Word\n\nIn Nepal, there isn't always a direct word for \"menopause\" used in daily conversation. You can\ndescribe it as \"the time of change\" or \"when the cycles stop.\" By using the word\n\"Menopause\" or explaining the process, you are teaching the next generation of girls (and boys)\nthat this is a normal, healthy part of life.\n\n      Remember: You are a team. When your family understands what is happening,\n      they can stop being confused and start being your support system.",
