    "id": "en-10-article-10-why-does-my-body-ache-during-menopause",
    "articleNumber": 10,
    "language": "english",
    "title": "Why does my body ache during menopause?",
    "summary": "When people talk about menopause, they usually mention hot flashes. But many women are surprised to find that their knees, fingers, hips, and back start to ache or feel \"stiff,\" especially first thing in the morning....",
    "content": "The \"Hidden\" Symptom\n\nWhen people talk about menopause, they usually mention hot flashes. But many women are\nsurprised to find that their knees, fingers, hips, and back start to ache or feel \"stiff,\" especially\nfirst thing in the morning.\n\nIn Nepal, women often say their body feels \"heavy\" or \"weak.\" There is a very specific biological\nreason for this.\n\n1. Estrogen: The Body's Natural \"Oil\"\n\nThink of estrogen as the \"oil\" that keeps your joints moving smoothly.\n\n   ● Reducing Swelling: Estrogen helps keep the inflammation (swelling) in your body low.\n   ● Protecting Cartilage: It protects the \"cushion\" between your bones.\n   ● The Change: When estrogen levels drop, your joints can become drier and more\n      swollen. This is why they feel \"stiff\" or \"rusty,\" like a door hinge that hasn't been oiled in\n      years.\n\n2. Muscle Tension and Stress\n\nBecause menopause can make you feel more stressed or anxious, your muscles stay \"tight\"\nwithout you realizing it.\n\n   ● Many women carry this tension in their shoulders and neck, leading to headaches.\n   ● If you aren't sleeping well because of night sweats, your muscles don't have time to\n      \"repair\" themselves at night, making the pain feel worse the next day.\n\n3. How can I feel better?\n\nYou don't always need strong painkillers. Try these steps first:\n\n   ● Keep Moving: It sounds strange, but the more you move, the more \"oil\" your joints\n      produce. A gentle 15-minute walk helps \"grease\" the joints.\n   ● Hydration: Your joints need water to stay cushioned. Drink plenty of water throughout\n      the day.\n   ● Warmth: A warm bath or a heating pad on sore areas can help relax tight muscles and\n      improve blood flow.\n\n   ● Turmeric (Besar): This common Nepali spice is famous for reducing swelling. Adding a\n      little to your warm milk or food is a great natural habit.\n\nWhen to See a Professional\n\nIf your joints are actually red and hot to the touch, or if the pain is so bad that you cannot walk\nor perform your daily chores, it is important to speak with a health professional to rule out other\nconditions like arthritis.\n\n      The Insight: Your body isn't \"breaking down\"; it is simply adjusting to a lower level\n      of its natural anti-inflammatory hormone. Gentle care and movement are your best\n      tools.",
