    "id": "en-11-article-11-can-i-have-symptoms-even-if-i-still-have-my-period",
    "articleNumber": 11,
    "language": "english",
    "title": "Can I have symptoms even if I still have my period?",
    "summary": "Most people think menopause is like a light switch: it’s either ON or OFF. But for most women, it is more like a sunset. The sun (your hormones) starts to go down slowly over several years before it finally disappears...",
    "content": "The \"Hidden\" Phase: Perimenopause\n\nMost people think menopause is like a light switch: it’s either ON or OFF. But for most women, it\nis more like a sunset. The sun (your hormones) starts to go down slowly over several years\nbefore it finally disappears.\n\nThis \"sunset\" phase is called Perimenopause. It can start 5 to 10 years before your periods\nstop completely.\n\n1. Yes, You Can Still Have Your Period\n\nDuring perimenopause, your ovaries are still working, but they are becoming \"unreliable.\"\n\n   ● The Rollercoaster: Some months you have a lot of estrogen, and other months you\n      have very little.\n   ● The Symptoms: Because your hormones are jumping up and down, you can have hot\n      flashes, mood swings, and trouble sleeping—even if you had a period just last week!\n\n2. How Your Periods Might Change\n\nIn Nepal, women often worry when their cycle changes. During this transition, it is normal to see:\n\n   ● The Timing: Your period might come every 21 days instead of 28, or it might skip two\n      months and then come back.\n   ● The Flow: One month might be very \"heavy\" (needing many pads), and the next might\n      be just light spotting.\n   ● The Duration: It might last for 3 days or 10 days.\n\n3. Why is this phase so stressful?\n\nPerimenopause is often more \"stormy\" than menopause itself.\n\n   ● Because your hormones are fluctuating wildly (instead of just being low), your mood\n      swings can feel much more intense.\n   ● You might feel fine one day and completely exhausted the next.\n\n4. Can I still get pregnant?\n\nYes. This is a very important point. As long as you are still having periods—even if they are\nirregular—you can still release an egg. If you do not wish to become pregnant, you should\ncontinue using contraception until you have gone 12 full months without any bleeding at all.\n\n      The Insight: If you are in your early 40s and feeling \"unlike yourself,\" don't wait for\n      your periods to stop before seeking support. Understanding that this is\n      Perimenopause can help you start taking care of your health early.",
